events.name: GDG Visalia - Game Programming Workshop
events.description:
Game Programming Workshop/Meetup/Indie Game Start

When: Five Friday Nights in October from 6 pm – 8 pm. Oct. 2, 9, 16 23 and 30th.

Location: Kaweah 204A 
Map link: http://goo.gl/YpiU1I
Map PDF: COS Visalia Map

Parking permit/ticket ($2 for the day pass) required.

Information:

Cost: FREE, we will use web-based open-source tools and software. 

What you need: 

• Basic Beginner HTML/JavaScript.
• GitHub.com account (free) and an email address.
• Interest in game programming and enthusiasm. 

What will we do?
SIGN UP (space is limited)
1. NO homework!
2. Learn Phaser.js – a 2d game framework – together by building a game using the free cloud9 web based IDE.
3. Work through this free book/tutorial individually OR in groups. ( https://leanpub.com/html5shootemupinanafternoon/read )
4. Earn a certificate upon completion and send your working game to friends.

events.name: GDG Valley DevFest 2016
events.description:
NOTE: BUY TICKETS HERE -> https://valleydevfest.com/

The biggest Google tech conference in the California Central Valley carefully crafted for you by GDG community! All about Android, Web and Cloud from the world experts. 

Google Developer Groups Fresno, Modesto, Oakdale, and Visalia have combined powers to offer a one day, 20+ talks, four parallel track extravaganza! Some of our speakers include:

• Paul Bakus, Web Developer Advocate at Google 

• Sandeep Dinesh, Cloud Developer Advocate at Google 

• Martin Omander, GDG Regional Lead North America at Google 

• Nilay Yener, Community Advocate at Google

• Murat Yener, Android Software Developer at Intel

• Justin Ribeiro, Google Developer Expert in Web, IoT, and Wearables 

• and so many more! https://valleydevfest.com/speakers 

We expect another +350 event this year and tickets are going fast! To attend the event, buy a ticket from https://www.eventbrite.com/e/valleydevfestcom-tickets-27337601502 or visit https://valleydevfest.com/ for more details.

We hope to see you there!

events.name: GDG Visalia - Google Trip
events.description:
Tour to the Google headquarters, but finally the chance is here for you to see all the famous building, sculptures and experience a being on the campus. We'll have a tour guide, and we'll visit the Google store as well. You don't need to have any technical proficiency for this event.

The definitive roster will be what I'll see on Eventbrite. Please head over there and register yourself and your guests:
https://www.eventbrite.com/e/2018-friday-google-trip-tickets-47196630392

If you choose to carpool with us you must be a student or notify us ahead of time to make accommodations. For freedom and liberty you can choose to carpool on your own (if you want to leave earlier, if it's more convenient for a smaller group, etc.). The only thing I ask is if you are about to come by COS Van then please don't pick that option on the ticket.

To simplify the budgeting on my end the Eventbrite fee does not contain the $13.50 (student discount) Computer History Museum tickets, so everyone would pay their own part there to the museum directly.

We'll have opportunity to get snacks at the Museum, at the rest stops at Case de Frutta. Please bring your snacks accordingly.

The agenda (rough):
https://docs.google.com/document/d/1AuFqXOf1jcni47t9WFxZkWSIkEp00SzDKfRi3TkYGwA

events.name: GDG Visalia
events.description:
Beginners welcome!
Location: John Muir 208 or 211 (upstairs)
Map link: http://goo.gl/GcofJs

Parking permits are: $2 for the day pass required

Greetings!
Join us at a combined FNL/GDG this Friday, February 1 in John Muir 208 starting at 5:30 pm. Food will be provided.

Our presentation will begin at 6 pm. If you missed last week, you missed the unboxing and initial tries with our new 3D scanner. We will show you some of the scans and 3D prints from that. John Redden will demonstrate and go over the code for a new programming project to create a repository for our 3D scans - upload, catalog and display. One idea is to scan in the skulls and bones for our anthropology professor, so they would be available for students to view outside of class. Take a look at the scan of the lower jaw of a sabertooth cat that was made last week.
https://fnlgames-8a375.firebaseapp.com/scanRepo/viewer.html

Some of you may have received some spam that appeared to come from FNLHub. If you did, we apologize and we are addressing the issue. We will include it as a topic of discussion for Friday night.

After the presentation, we will continue working in project groups. We have some great projects in the works, but we will also have a discussion on new project ideas. So, if you are not currently working on a project, but you want to, now is the time to jump in and get on a project team. We want to have several projects completed and ready to present at the COS STEMposium in August. If you have an idea, let us know about it. Newcomers are always welcome! Bring a friend.

FNL runs until about 10 pm. Drop in for any part of the evening if you can't stay the whole time.

I hope to see you there!

GDG time: 7:30 pm

Greetings!
This week at FNL will be on a different schedule, so please read this message.

We are encouraging everyone to attend the MESA STEM recognition ceremony in the Ponderosa Lecture hall at 5:00 pm to honor our STEM students for academic achievement and for our transferring students. The ceremony will end at about 6:15 pm.

Attend the reception following the MESA ceremony in the FNL room (JM 208) immediately following the ceremony. We will have food and demos for everyone - regular FNL'ers, our honored students, and their guests. The FNL lab will not open until after the ceremony is over.

We will have a short Google Developers Group (GDG) presentation at 7:30 pm - everyone is welcome to stay! It will be a general talk that everyone can use - doing advanced searches on Google.

Following the presentation, we will get to work on projects in our usual productive manner.

SCHEDULE SUMMARY:
MESA STEM Honors Ceremony in Ponderosa Hall: 5:00-6:15 pm
RECEPTION with food and demos in John Muir 208: 6:30-7:30 pm
Google Advanced Searches GDG Presentation in John Muir 208: 7:30-8:00 pm
FNL project work 8:00-closing

FNL runs until about 10 pm. Drop in for any part of the evening if you can't stay the whole time.

I hope to see you there!

Parking permits are: $2 for the day pass required
